In many campaigns, a spaceship is an adventure location; even more
commonly, it's a home base. The PCs will spend a lot of time there,
and the GM will often want adventure scenes to play out on board the
ship, or on board other ships.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Star Trek did very well with only the slimmest actual details of how
&gt; the Enterprise worked.
">

Yet there were also many episodes set largely on board the ship, and
it's a hugely common trope of the genre.

If the adventure calls for the PCs to roam around a ship -- ours,
theirs or disputed -- as a scene in the adventure, you need to
convince them they're *on the ship*. A keyed deck plan then becomes
just as important as any other keyed adventure map.

If the PCs use the ship as a mobile home base, the players are going
to be interested in knowing what goes where. Even if no adventure
scenes are planned on board, it's very helpful to the players'
imagination to be able to picture the place they inhabit.

