I'm with Douglas here, the new 4e trend of "genre" books (Fantasy,
Space), that are very sparse on commitments to particular settings,
dovetails nicely with the all-about-one-setting books (Banestorm,
Interstellar Wars).

I'm glad that the material in the book called "Space" is broadly
applicable to a great range of settings, rather than having a sizeable
portion of the book dedicated to material far more specific than the
rest.

It seems to me that people are mostly annoyed because, in spite of the
plentiful commentary online about how the 4e genre books are *not*
complete replacements for the 3e books of the same name, these people
still have a strong expectation from the 3e book contents.

The only way to avoid that would be to release these books with
*different* names; but I don't think that's worth the price. With SJG
publishing a book that's all about the multitude of Space campaigns
with the GURPS system, and nothing about any particular setting, I
don't want that book called anything else but "GURPS Space".

If anything, this just shows that the equivalent books for 3e were the
ones with the mismatched title-to-content.

