Actually, I think the problem is slightly different.

One of the lessons that SJG learned from 3e is that when you really
need new rules or new systems, multiple authors will develop them
independently, and they'll be incompatible.  People don't like that.
The alternative is developing them once and then duplicating them, and
people *really* don't like that.  So one of the decisions they made
for 4e was that all the rules for vehicle construction would be in one
place, all the rules for high-tech weaponry would be in one place, and
so on.  This makes a lot of sense, and solves the two problems they
were trying to avoid.

But what they didn't anticipate was the production speed.  They wrote
Space with the idea that the rules for building starships would be in
a later Vehicles supplement and the rules for high-tech weapons would
be in a later Ultra-Tech supplement.  Unfortunately, there are no
announced Vehicles supplements that I know of, and Ultra-Tech is not
quite out yet.

(My own solution is to Make Stuff Up, but that annoys people who want
to run a long campaign and don't want to have to retcon everything
in 2 years when official stats are published.)

