Only in that a writer has totally control over *all* the characters unless
it is a retelling of a RPG (Lodoss War for example).  Also if a writer goes
too far afield in handling characters they don't tend to do well.  This is
more apparent with long established characters than 'one shots'.  For
example Sir Arthur Conan Doyle wrote a stage play where Holmes was so OOC
that it bombed and so he turned it into what is generally regarded as the
worse story in the canon: The Mazarin Stone.  Marvel did something just as
bad with Spiderman and the Clone Saga.

Additionally most RPGs have cinematic elements in them where GMs have to
'fudge' the die rolls so the PCs don't become stains on the landscape just
because they rolled bad (as opposed to doing something out right stupid)
